<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>4 Beresford Avenue</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Freight on Rail (SRN 004)</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freight on Rail thanks the Transport Select Committee for the opportunity to comment on its inquiry into the strategic road network.  We are commenting on 3 of the subject headings.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Government must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">look at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">multi-modal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">solutions along </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">key strategic corridors with significant lorry traffic, in order to meet its economic, environmental and safety g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oals. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Therefore it must </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">consider rail freight options in the route based strategies and in the feasibility studies. Because r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">oad and rail complement each other rail freight has a key role in helping the Government reduce road congestion</span><a name="_ednref1"></a><a href="#_edn1">[i]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and meet its road</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> safety</span><a name="_ednref2"></a><a href="#_edn2">[ii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and emissions</span><a name="_ednref3"></a><a href="#_edn3">[iii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> targets especially on key arterial freight routes. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">can offer an alternative integrated solution for the T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ranspennine route, A303/A30 corridor, the A1 west and north of Newcastle and around Leeds</span><a name="_ednref4"></a><a href="#_edn4">[iv]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Multi-modal transport options should be evaluated to  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">address future problems including the five transport hotspots</span><a name="_ednref5"></a><a href="#_edn5">[v]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Rail freight alternatives were assessed to some extent in the A14 corridor study</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2012, the intermodal analysis of the A14 corrido</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r showed that there was considerable suppressed demand for rail out of the Felixstowe port because of the current limitations of the rail network and it highlighted the value of implementing rail capacity upgrades on the A14. These enhancements were subseq</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uently included in the HLOS funding for the CP5 period. The evaluation showed that the extra capacity, would allow daily trains operations in and out of the port each day to increase from 30 to 50 which will increase rail’s market share increasing from 25%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to around 38%. Furthermore, these upgrades will result in the removal of 40 million long distance lorry miles from the A14 corridor per annum. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Targeted rail freight upgrades work; rai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l’s market share out of Southampton port increased from 29-36% withi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n a year of completion of the gauge upgrade demonstrating the direct benefits of rail enhancements</span><a name="_ednref6"></a><a href="#_edn6">[vi]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The CEO of HPUK, Clemence Cheung, told </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the Transport Select Committee hearing on Access to Ports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">earlier in the year</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that improved rail capacity was key</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to Felixstowe port and would improve the competitive position of the port relative to ports such as Rotterdam. He said that less than three per cent of containers from the port were transported via the A14.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">5. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Work with rail freight industry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">to achieve </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">tegrated solution </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfT Roads directorate should work with Network Rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the Focs, RFG</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and the Rail Delivery Group to ensure that an integrated approach is adopted</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on key corridors as r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ail freight links are an important driver of economic regeneration w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hich can help the Coalition Government meet its transport objective to promote the green sustainable economy with green jobs. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">RFG/RFOA commissioned rail freight forecasts which showed that  traffic overall is expected to double in the period between 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and 2030 with consumer traffic growing four fold.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As you will be aware, Network Rail has undertaken a comprehensive Freight market study</span><a name="_ednref7"></a><a href="#_edn7">[vii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which includes forecasts for growth, due to be released later this year which can be fed into these feasibility studies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Planned </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ail freight enhancements must be taken into account</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is also crucial that the existing committed enhancements for the rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> network are taken into consideration when planning the strategic road network. The Government has committed to a series of upgrades in the Control Period 5 which must be taken into account. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£200m for the Strategic (Rail) Freight Network (SFN)</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Additionall</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y, the following projects are the main schemes which will benefit freight and passenger services:- </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ii) Reconstruction of Ely North Junction </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iii) Leicester area capacity</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">iv) Electric Spin – Southampton Port to Basingstoke, Basingstoke – Reading- Oxford –B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">anbury – Leamington Spa – Coventry</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">v) Capacity upgrades to the West and East Coast Mainline</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vi) Great Western electrification</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Released capacity on WCML for freight as a result of HS2 </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The benefits of using </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> at least three extra freight paths per hour off </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">peak</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on the WCML from released capacity should be taken into account</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">B</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">. How can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network?</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Shifting more freight to rail reduces road congestion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and exposure to road collisions </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hich c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rucially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">improves </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reliability as recognised by the Government Mode Shift grants system. The following statistics demonstrate the role rail has in alleviating road congestion; an average consumer freight train can remove up to 60 HGVs from our  roads </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and an aggregates train can remove up to 130 HGVs from our roads. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Contradictions in DfT Freight Policy  </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">olicies such as the  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">DfT’s decision to allow trials of 7ft longer lorries, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which its own research stated would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">undermine</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rail freight a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> encourage more road freight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">contradicts its stated policy to promote rail freight and reduce road collisions and pollution.  Because longer trailers will </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">result in more external costs, more unreliability and more congestion on the strategic road network.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The DfT central case for longer trailers was built on the prediction that road operators will increase their share of goods traffic as a result of introducing longer lorries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In particular, consumer rail freight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a key growth market</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> using the DfT figures be severely undermined</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and forecasted growth would be cut by two thirds.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">DfT research stated - </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lower rail use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">was</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> a major source of benefits in having longer trailers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Between 27% to 32% of the environmental benefits of longer trail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ers are assumed to be gained by running fewer trains. By 2025 - 84% of the industry operational savings would be from lower rail costs. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The assessment is very sensitive to the way that less rail traffic translates into fewer train kilometers and a realisti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c picture would be of external costs rising significantly. Also, if trains were electrified or became quieter, the benefits of not running them would fall and so would the benefits of longer trailers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Longer trailers would undermine low carbon energy-effi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cient rail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly the emerging supermarket (domestic intermodal) rail traffic, the sector with the highest growth potential of up to 12 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">times in a 25 year period </span><a name="_ednref8"></a><a href="#_edn8">[viii]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Even the DfT figures states that the 2 metre trailer would reduce rail freight growt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h by two thirds (down from 732% to 262%) by 2025. This is because the relative costs of road and rail will be adversely affected by the new units, and rail will face a cost disadvantage; savings of up to 15% are predicted by some in the road haulage indust</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ry. However the DfT suggest that this impact would be offset by rail operator being able to use longer intermodal units than at present, increasing their own efficiencies.  However, this assumes that customers will want to invest in such units, ahead of in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vesting in road fleet and also that the existing equipment, much of which is new, can be written off. All this is likely to result in a downward spiral for rail freight in this sector as critical mass is lost.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Longer trucks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ould mean more lorry miles not fewer </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">because demand will be stimulated as longer trailers would reduce road haulage costs by up to 13%. Distribution centre are likely to be rationalised, saving on real estate costs, with lorry tonne kilometres increasing a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">s the same freight is carried further.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">The economic assumptions in the report are not realistic as they underestimate the extent to which longer vehicles will add to road mileage. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Longer trailers will be slower to negotiate road junctions and add to road </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">congestion</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The actual length of traffic lane occupied and the time that the lane is occupied needs to be fully taken into account. HGVs are considered to take up almost 4 times the space of an average car when stationery (passenger car units). Then one has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to allow for the fact that HGVs are slower to negotiate junctions and need longer front and rear headway than cars as braking distances are greater.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">C  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">re there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">1. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Distance based lorry road user charging </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Freight on Rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">supports</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the principal of introducing a lorry road user charging system to ensure ensures fairer arrangements for the UK haulage industry. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At present UK hauliers face unfair competition, with foreign hauliers not paying anything towards the costs of their use of U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">K roads. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, we believe that the Government’s chosen time based system charges foreign hauliers too little, because of the EU restrictions, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it raises. We believe that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he Go</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vernment should instead have gone for a distance-based charging scheme, as most European countries are now doing. This would charge foreign lorries properly for using UK roads, and would raise revenue that could be used to fund a more efficient and greener</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> UK freight industry. We therefore urge the Government to consider a comprehensive distance based system which could actually help reduce road congestion, emissions, accidents a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s well as raising revenue. </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Disadvantages of the Time based system </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">being introd</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">uced next April 2014</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given that foreign hauliers only account for 6% of UK vehicle miles, the administrative burden of this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scheme </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both for UK operators and DfT seems too high and could end up actually costing more in administration and enforcement than it</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> raises.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A simple but effective distance based  lorry road user charging scheme would therefore be fairer to UK hauliers but could also deliver wider objectives to:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Improve road safety</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Reduce greenhouse gas emissions</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">• Minimise the external costs from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">heavy good vehicle traffic, including local air pollution, noise and congestion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The experience from Europe shows that lorry road user charging schemes can be introduced, that the technology is proven and that this delivers significant benefits, particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly to support the economy and reduce climate change – the two main objectives in the new Government’s transport policies.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The German Maut system</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, developed within the Eurovignette guidelines, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reduced empty running by 11% down to under 20%, increased rail f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reight by 7% and loaded runs by 2.1% in the ten year period up to 2010. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a href="http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/campaigns/climate_change/roads/lorry-user-charging"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.bettertransport.org.uk/campaigns/climate_change/roads/lorry-user-charging</span></a></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Appendix</span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further benefits of rail freight which should be taken into account in transport infrastructure development</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Freight Transport: Average emissions in grams per tonne-kilometre</span></p><table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" style="border-collapse:collapse; margin-left:0pt"><tr><td style="vertical-align:top; width:73.5pt"><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; f